                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d859">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">856B.01/5: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Curaçao</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Huddleston</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Curaçao</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-05-12T10:00:00-04:30"
                            >May 12, 1940—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 4:38 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Reference is made to the Department’s telegram May 10, midnight [<hi
                        rend="italic">noon?</hi>] and to my telegram of May 10, 3 p.m.<note n="8"
                        xml:id="d859fn8">Neither printed.</note> The British cruiser <hi
                        rend="italic">Despatch</hi> arrived at Willemstad at 5 p.m., May 11. A
                    proclamation of the Governor of Curaçao, states that as part of The Netherlands
                    this territory is also at war with the German Reich but that its international
                    political status will remain as before; that the Government established here has
                    resolved to continue to remain in and to take care of this part of the
                    Netherlands territory on land and at sea and any help from outside from whomever
                    it may come will be refused and considered as unwelcome.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Huddleston</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
